I don’t like that. I like my logged values to represent raw data and not calculated data even if that calculation is simply the raw data minus a constant.

So, when I implemented this template into my own code I switched it so that when the robot starts it resets the SparkMax encoder to the the value it should be given the value of the offset and the current rotation of the module wheel. This allows me to get rid of that .minus in line 197 and just record the raw value of the position of the SparkMax.

But I forgot to see where else that zero rotation is applied. Once I looked for it I found it in the code that feeds the odometry thread that ends up being used to calculate the robot pose.

ifOk(turnSpark, turnSpark::getOutputCurrent, (value) -> inputs.turnCurrentAmps = value);

inputs.turnConnected = turnConnectedDebounce.calculate(!sparkStickyFault);

// Update odometry inputs

inputs.odometryTimestamps =

timestampQueue.stream().mapToDouble((Double value) -> value).toArray();

inputs.odometryDrivePositionsRad =

drivePositionQueue.stream().mapToDouble((Double value) -> value).toArray();

inputs.odometryTurnPositions =

turnPositionQueue.stream()

.map((Double value) -> new Rotation2d(value).minus(zeroRotation))

.toArray(Rotation2d[]::new);

timestampQueue.clear();

drivePositionQueue.clear();

turnPositionQueue.clear();

}

@Override

public void setDriveOpenLoop(double output) {

driveSpark.setVoltage(output);

}

Just has to get rid of that .minus and all issues were resolved.
